rComments: Prof. Mike provided all lecture code on GitHub. He was very helpful when asked questions. His lectures are decent & cover all topics, assignments/tests have a clear grading criteria. Some labs took a lot of time due to confusing instructions/lack of clarity for what the question is asking. Overall, the course was interesting and I learned a ton.

The prof himself is great. Have a clear explanation of the course material and programming in general, very responsive & helpful outside of class time.

However, do notice that this course is not easy. Assignments are hard, labs are hard (but reasonable) and tests are in a heavy time constraint. Do prepare to study a lot if you want a good grade
teacherRatingTags: ['Clear grading criteria', 'Accessible outside class', 'Gives good feedback']

rComments: He used a mixture of powerpoint slides and coding when teaching which was really intuitive, assignments basically hold your hand but can be wordy. The coding questions for the midterm/ exam were fair and he told us what we needed to focus on, but the multi-choice was a different story.He also hosted 4 exam reviews which helped a lot. Overall good.

Although it is labeled as an introductory programming course, this course is not an easy course. I cannot tell you how much I have learnt this semester though; big thanks to both the professor and my hard work. Make sure to complete and understand all labs. Overall, keep up. Best of luck!

He's very bad, the material and work are all extremely hard and poorly written. The exams for the last term were made easier due to the high failure rate. His lectures are useless as he talks about Java 3 when the entire class is using java 11. Noting is relevant, you are better off learning on your own through w3school for java than the prof.

The content of this course can be challenging for many students who are coding for the first time in Java. Do not expect to learn everything directly from the professor, however; the labs and assignments are clear in their instructions and definitely help you learn. External resources will be your best friend, the case with most coding classes.

Doesn't know how to teach at all even if you have done python or any programming language before this guy will make it really really hard for you to understand be ready to use YouTube as your best friend.

Lectures are just YouTube tutorials and the actual zoom meeting is useless. he doesn't teach and that's why only 6 people show up for the synchronous lecture. All your work is auto graded by a program an 11th grader wrote and it gives u a 0 for the whole assignment/lab if his test fails. He doesn't answer questions, just dodges them like faker.

Doesn't explain basics well and moves quickly into concepts as opposed to implementations. You need to study on your own if you haven't used Java before. Caring guy that answers questions thoroughly during lectures but you can read the slides yourself and get through the content way quicker. Assignments slightly more confusing than ITI 1120.
The prof genuinely cares about his students and answers their questions very well.

Okay, first he explains using slides 90% of the time and this is a programming course!! Yes some students have background in Java, however some DONT!! the 10 % where he actually explains using a code he would have it already written instead of walking you through the process to actually understand the syntax. Be prepared to watch YT JAVA TUTS

His assignment and midterm were more advanced for beginner programmers in the language java. To be honest there isn't a good teacher to teach ITI1121. He wouldn't post the solution to labs or midterms and was very secretive about what was going to be on the midterm. This isn't an introduction this is so advanced for beginners. AVOID FOR THIS CLASS!
I am wondering does uottawa has a good professor to teach ITI 1121

Horrible class. Firstly there was three different places to retrieve stuff about your class that it just got so complicated just to find the syllabus. The lectures were no help and ended up watching youtube to self-teach myself. But the worst part was the grading. The grading was very poor as they never give you enough time and marked hard.

The lectures themselves are okay, however the labs, assignments and tests are really hard. Barely enough time to finish the work for the tests. This is not an easy course, so if it's not mandatory, do not take it. Even if you're straight A+ student, it will lower your GPA and your self-esteem.

Professor Sabetzadeh, along with professor Jourdan did a fair job on ITI 1121. Both assignments and tests are heavy. However, he cares about his students, answering their questions on piazza. For assignments, it is long and not explained very well, need time to "decipher" from the assignment's PDF.

Prof. Sabetzadeh genuinely cares about the success of the students(always answers on piazza in detail). The professors made a mistake writing the questions for the midterm by making them much too involved for the allotted time. This issue was fixed on the final. The exam was reasonably challenging and fair.

I do not recommend taking Java with this professor. He does the bare minimum, doesn't code in the class, reads code, and makes the exams way harder than assignments and labs. Also he told a lot of his students to drop his course.

Professor Mehrdad really cares about his students and is always on top of the questions posted on piazza. He even will talk with 1 on 1 if you're struggling. I found that his lectures are very boring but teaches everything you need to know. Also his assignments are not explained very well, I've spent ALOT of time trying to understand them.
Lectures are boring, exams are BRUTAL. Labs are somewhat useful. This course is a necessary evil.
Why are they making ITI 1121 harder? That's not even an introduction to computing.

I was very exciting to do ITI 1121. He is new at the University of Ottawa. I search him on rate my professor. He hasn't have any review. I decided to give him a chance. He was the worst Professor I ever seem. I finally drop the class one month before the final. I did the Midterm, It was very long and very hard to understand. Avoid this prof.
I did not attend a single class, but just went through the notes by myself and passed with a high grade.

Uses an automated system to grade labs, tests, and assignments. Instructions are unclear and any error results in a zero. Will tell you to send him an email if you have questions regarding a grade. Will not reply to said email or otherwise address it.

Both professor Guy Vincent and Mehrdad's assignments, labs, and final exam are the same. Both teaching style is not really different. This course title is Introduction to Computing but they are teaching at an advanced level but you cannot blame the professor for that. You need to really work hard and have basic knowledge to get good grades in class

When you think of a programming class, you usually expect to spend more time understanding the code and how to code, rather than spending over 99 percent of the time deciphering what the instructions want us to do. Well not here, get ready to spend a good week understanding the assignment PDF and Labs. Highly suggest a different professor.
